At the ecosystem level climate change is expected not only to affect the diversity of native fauna and flora, but also the ecosystems that provide goods and services for human welfare and development. Extreme climatic conditions relevant for the marine biodiversity sector include:
* sea-level rise;
* higher sea surface temperatures;
* increasingly frequent and intense tropical storms;
* frequent flooding;
* extreme high and low tides; and
* increases in ocean acidification.
* habitat mortality: coral bleaching, erosion, and sedimentation;
* accelerated coastal erosion that will remove beaches and mangroves important
* extensive coastal inundation and higher levels of sea flooding;
* waves and storm surges into coastal land areas, causing salinity in coastal
* mangroves and wetlands pushed further inland by frequent king tides and
* eutrophication, sedimentation and siltation of water resources, leading to
* increased habitat and nursery areas destruction, ensuing in species decline;
* decline in inshore fisheries; and loss of natural reefs that protect the islands
* replanting mangroves and restoring habitats;
* re-introducing native and endemic plants within established national reserves
* improving the way protection regimes for marine and terrestrial biodiversity
* reviewing the way different laws, policies, and strategies are implemented.
